##On Earth | from Hubei 13 counties and cities, sent 300 medical workers back to Wuhan to fight the epidemic

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Phoenix News Client, produced by Phoenix Network Studio on Earth

My name is Fan Cao Jun. I am 34 years old and I am from Zaoyang, Xiangyang, Hubei Province. I have been studying and working in Wuhan for more than ten years. Wuhan is my second hometown.

Last December, I began to pay attention to the sporadic outbreaks in the south China Seafood Market. Because of my job, I often run around in Wuhan. Once, in January, I was driving by the south China Seafood Market, and there were so many medical workers and police and Chengguan, and the market had been closed, that I realized the epidemic was getting worse.

I bought a disposable surgical mask that same day. My friends in Wuhan also knew about it, but since the government made it clear at the time that it wouldn't pass from one person to another, a few of our friends wouldn't wear masks when they were together, only when they were out.

I returned to Zaoyang a few days ago, twenty-nine of the New Year, the city of Wuhan was closed. I was at home, and I woke up this morning, and I was shocked. Just think, not misread it, how will the entire Wuhan to the closure?

At that time I couldn't understand what it meant to close the city. All I know is that Wuhan is such a big city. The third ring road adds up to nearly 80 kilometers, and it takes more than an hour to drive around it. The Fourth Ring Road is more than 150 kilometers, not counting the surrounding districts such as Huangpi District and Jiangxia District.

At this point, I think things are getting serious, the epidemic continues to escalate, the news figures are exploding. Wuhan medical staff several days and nights without rest, directly lying on the floor asleep, and even sacrifice of medical staff.

Then, many hospitals in Wuhan began to call their staff back for vacation or rest. One after another, I saw that many medical staff in many counties and cities in Hubei urgently needed to return to Wuhan.

But at that time everyone focused on Wuhan, did not pay much attention to the peripheral front, such as other cities and counties in the province to support the medical staff, our city has many. I figured since no one's doing it, we'll do it.

One

During the past Spring Festival, even if there is no epidemic, Hubei's county-level cities and towns, hitchhiking is very inconvenient, not to mention in the outbreak of the city in the case of village closure.

The first day, I in fellow Wechat Group and friends of the message, call conditional friends when the driver volunteers, send medical staff to Wuhan to work. I have seven or eight villages in Zaoyang, including Zaoyang People in Wuhan, a total of about 2,000 or 3,000 people, there are many medical staff, there are many drivers.

The call was soon answered and a team of 25 volunteers was formed that night. I've never met any of these 25 people, they're mostly private car owners, they have jobs, but they're very enthusiastic.

But I came back from Wuhan to be quarantined at my home in Zaoyang. I couldn't get out of the house, so I stayed home and did command work. I put together a group of 25 drivers.

It was easy to assemble the motorcade, and the follow-up organization and implementation process were difficult.

On the 2nd day, we sent two cars for a test drive. I did a little outreach, and a paramedic responded immediately. She is a nurse in a hospital in Wuhan, now in Zaoyang, at first the hospital did not ask them to go back, but she learned the situation in the group in Wuhan, offered to go back to Wuhan support.

At first, the medics had to go back on their own. Later, the situation in Wuhan became more and more critical, more and more medical staff asked to go back, and we became busier and busier.

After a medical worker took a ride with us, he would send information about the volunteers of our convoy to their medical care group, which was passed on from one to the next. Later, there was a group of medical care workers from the province who returned to Wuhan formed by other enthusiastic volunteers, when Xiangyang returned to Wuhan, for example, we were invited to join the group, and the network was slowly built.

It is more than 300 kilometers from Zaoyang to Wuhan and a three-hour one way trip. At first, our driver was only in Zaoyang, but then it quickly spread to the surrounding counties, about 13 of them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
 Su Hongchang, the owner of the shoe factory, sent five medical workers from Zaoyang, Suizhou, Yunmeng and Xiaogan counties to Wuhan. At the fuhe Toll Station, the traffic police took photos of them.

The whole thing was pretty rough. As the outbreak escalated, all traffic was blocked from the province to the city, from the city to the county, and even from the village. My home in the countryside, the village also began to post notice at the door, registration, report.

There's a lot of hard work involved in coordinating a paramedic from the village to the town, to the city, to our meeting point.

There was a woman doctor who was working in Wuhan, in a village in Xiaochang County, going back to work in Wuhan. I talked to her before we left so we could figure out where to go. Because we send more. We have experience. She didn't know what to do, so I instructed her, like, what kind of papers to get from the hospital, how to get them opened, whether to get them stamped, how to communicate with the locals.

The next day, just as she was driving out of the village, she was stopped. She talked to the village for a long time but couldn't help it. Later, I explained to the people in her village that we were a team of volunteers for public welfare. Our car had reached the junction of the highway, and we were going to take the doctor back to Wuhan to participate in the fight against the epidemic. It took me a while to let her out.

Not far from the village, she encountered a lot of road closures. Road closures in the countryside are violent. Get a bulldozer or a pile of dirt and block up the whole road. She asked me what to do, and I said You should call your dad or a relative and get a motorcycle and meet us at Xiaochang County and Xiaogan.

Along the way, from village to town, from town to town, across the region after another pass, was stopped by the local traffic police. She explained to the traffic police for a long time, it's no use, no, just can't go. Traffic police did not approve of the hospital's certificate, said that now the top has issued a death order.

She cried and asked me what to do. I thought about it and said, you can call 110,120, the mayor's hotline, or the local 12345 at the scene. She called 110.110. She didn't say no. She didn't say no. In the end, the traffic police was moved by US, and looked at her relevant evidence, including our chat records, confirmed that this person is back to Wuhan support, just released. The traffic police took her in their car to meet our motorcade driver at the junction of the highway.

The doctor posted a message on her facebook page, to the effect that she had traveled all the way across mountains and rivers to make a real life version of lost on the road, where she used virtually all means of transportation except ships and planes.

Two

A lot of times I just pick up a piece of paper, get a phone call, get a pen and start writing. What is his screen name, where is he, when will he probably leave, where is the nearest highway intersection from him, how many cars we have left, which cars we can get, what number is the driver's phone number, and when do we need to meet him there, which Way's the fastest? Wait. Everything we could think of, I took it into account.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
 Cui Wei (second from left, a veteran and self-made entrepreneur) , is always the first to escort medical staff.

It didn't start out that way. Initially, either an enthusiastic volunteer or a paramedic would drop a message in the group, which hospital I was from, where I was going, where I was, or a volunteer would tell me where my car was, how empty it was, where it was going.

It's peer-to-peer communication, and it's very inefficient, especially in groups of hundreds of people, and it's easy to take the screen and make the information invisible to the people who really need it.

The first two times we communicated like this, but the next day I immediately changed the way I worked. I figured out a way for me to set up the hub backstage, with my left hand on the driver and my right hand on the paramedics. Drivers and paramedics do not contact each other until the information is confirmed. When I determined that the basic match was above 90% , I pulled up a small group of drivers, myself, and the paramedic in the car.

I'll plan the route in advance, first where to pick up the paramedics, and second which paramedics to pick up. That way, the driver only has to remember what time it is, what intersection to pick up the paramedics, say, two people in Zaoyang, two people at a Suizhou toll booth. The driver doesn't need to contact one by one to confirm the details of the medical staff. When the medical staff is in trouble, they don't need to ask for help from the driver. They only need to ask for help from me. I will tell them how to get to the assembly point. The driver can wait patiently, this greatly increases the efficiency of the delivery. We can do almost every car full, a five seater private car can seat four health care workers, a seven seater commercial vehicle or an MPV can seat five to six people.

I'll route the driver through the group, and I'll be contacted by medical personnel along the way. I worked almost 17 or 18 hours a day, keeping an eye on the dynamics of the group, the contacts, the coordination, the design of the routes.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
 Deng Guotao, a printer, escorted medical personnel from Gucheng County and Yibin back to Wuhan for support.

By rough count, we've sent almost 300 paramedics so far. We have about 20 or 30 drivers. Today's cars, tomorrow's cars, take a day off in principle, and those who are particularly dedicated run continuously, once a day, without a break.

Most of the drivers were from Zaoyang, and then from other places, Gucheng County, Yicheng, etc. . They came to us through other channels, maybe they didn't have a local organization, or they didn't have local volunteers, and they came to us, because we have a bigger team and we have more information.

One of our local drivers in Zaoyang, he's been signing up since I started the call. We helped him coordinate with the village, gave him all kinds of papers, but the locals wouldn't let him out. Every day he watched the group to transport the ambulance driver so hard, anxious, unable to help, he has been around for four or five days, with the village, with the mayor of the call, with the city coordination, ultimately unsuccessful. Every place has its own protective needs, which we understand, but I'm touched by his spirit.

A neighborhood security guard told the driver, you can take this car out, after driving out, do not drive back, the driver was very helpless, said, good, then I do not drive back.

So far, two of our drivers have pulled out. It's not that they want out, it's that their families are worried about their safety, and they can't help it. We can understand that.

Three

There were questions along the way. Some people say that you have a national calamity, this time to go out to the roadster business, or that the government to give you a subsidy, a day two thousand. All kinds of things. The truth is, we don't have any money.

I've faced this kind of skepticism before when I was a blood donor. I am a volunteer of "the volunteer team of free blood donation in Qinyi" in Wuhan. I have donated more than 30 times, three times a year on average. Not only to participate in their own unpaid blood donation, but also to influence more people around to join.

Once I took three or four of my friends to donate blood and posted them on my facebook page. Someone said, you take so many people to donate blood, how much do they each pay you? It means how much money does the blood center give me when I send someone to donate blood. I'm sorry to hear that.

 Fan Caojun, a private motorcade organizer, donated platelets at the Wuhan Blood Center.

All the services are pro bono, and there's no profit in it.

Of course, at first the drivers offered to give the paramedics away for free. I thought about it, and decided that it wasn't realistic to give them away for free, because a 600 kilometer trip meant that any car would have to pay five hundred bucks a trip for gas. These drivers are ordinary wage earners, five hundred yuan he can afford, but he can afford a few four or five hundred dollars.

I decided to charge a nominal fee to keep the business running smoothly for a long time. The bus from Zaoyang to Wuhan costs $100 a seat, and our car carries the paramedic for $50. Barely saved my gas money.

I never touch the money. I'll tell the paramedics that you're in the car, or when you get to your destination, send it to a small group (each car has a small group) and remind the driver to collect it. The paramedics understood. We won't say how much it costs, but they will pay, and they will pay more.

We have done more, and one after another, some warm-hearted citizens from Zaoyang and Wuhan have donated, although it is not much, thousands of yuan, but every time the driver goes out of the car, I will give them 50 yuan of gas money, as a sign of respect for the people who care about them.

On 5 February, the convoy was suspended. It has to do with the news that he hui, the volunteer driver, has died. We don't know him, but he's one of us. Upon hearing the news, the group began to discuss how to protect themselves. Because we are in contact with more people, if we are carriers of the virus, it is not infected with the medical staff.

We haven't had much protection. I made it clear to everyone when we started this, it's all voluntary. But I would make sure they had proper protection, like wearing a mask and keeping the car as well ventilated as possible while driving. Before you leave, disinfect your car once, once at the Wuhan Toll Booth after talking to the local traffic police and volunteers, and again when you return to Zaoyang. On average, each car is disinfected two or three times a day.

We had no protective clothing from the beginning, and now we have no masks or alcohol, so we have to suspend operations. I announced the news in the group, also told the driver, must do everything possible to raise supplies, is particularly touched, a driver said, as long as the protective supplies arrived, we immediately start.

When I saw the video of a female doctor who had spent four days and three nights cycling 300 kilometers back to her job in Wuhan, I was in tears. Only those who have gone through the process know how hard it is. "I can't bear to see a second 'doctor cycling back to Wuhan' . "

Then, I wrote a paragraph in the group of volunteer drivers, said that from today on, to do everything possible to help you raise supplies, supplies after the collection would like to continue to do voluntary registration.

On February 7, we raised 170 disposable face masks, 50 goggles, 50 bottles of rubbing alcohol, but still no protective clothing. In the evening I called on the group to restart the convoy on February 11 to continue transporting medical staff, and drivers have responded.

Four

I remember very well that the year after high school, the first time I went to Wuhan, a few classmates and I dragged our luggage out of the Hankou Railway Station, took the No. 803 bus, walked around Hankou, then took Jianghan Bridge, and then walked to Hanyang. The longest bus ride between Xiangyang and Zaoyang was no more than half an hour, but it took us a full hour and a half to get there. On the way, we asked the bus driver whether he had arrived, whether he had arrived or not. We were afraid that we would miss the bus stop. The bus driver got bored and said in the Wuhan Dialect, "I will call you when I get there. I will not miss it. ". Then we joked about it, saying it was a good deal, two bucks for an hour and a half.

The city is very big, many universities, all universities are very beautiful, very cultural atmosphere. That year, Urban village was everywhere in Wuhan, including the bustling part of the city. Many friends from other places joked with me that Wuhan is a big rural area. I joked with them at that time, saying, then you are right, we are from the countryside. We like Wuhan very much, the countryside on the countryside Bai, from the small countryside to the big countryside.

After coming to Wuhan, I thought, first the work is stable down, then want to study, go to a university. I stopped studying after high school because of my family's finances, and then I moved to Kyushu to work for Tong pharmaceuticals.

At that time, the company to help employees to improve their education, organized everyone to go to college, I took the initiative to apply, we will work side to the university. Four and a half years and an undergraduate degree. It was my first job, too. The pharmaceutical company is in the fight against the epidemic, the official takeover of the Hubei Red Cross warehouse that pharmaceutical company. I worked there for seven or eight years, and they are absolutely the most professional in Hubei Province in the management, distribution and distribution of medical supplies.

I am now working in an insurance company. I have lived in Wuhan for many years. I like it here very much.

Wuhan is actually a very beautiful city, not as they say big countryside, not at all. In terms of cultural heritage, Wuhan Has Wuhan University, Huake, 211,985, no worse than any other city in China. In terms of scenery, there are 5A class scenic spots, the Yangtze River bridge, Yellow Crane Tower, and national scenic spots, including the later East L. Greenway and so on.

Now every day in the group medical staff to seek back to Wuhan vehicles, February 8 I counted a day 25 people. I want to raise protective gear and start the convoy as soon as possible.

I hope the epidemic will soon be over and Wuhan will soon return to its original state. If possible, I work hard and buy a house and settle down in Wuhan.
